These Pseudo-Acronian Scholia he relegates to the 5th century. The ‘ editio princeps ' is not certainly known: the title is usually given to an edition without name or date, which is supposed to have been published by Zarotus at Milan in 1470. The first edition, which contains a commentary by a modern scholar of name, is that of Landinus (Cristoforo Landin0‚ born at Florence 1424, died 1504), printed at Florence in 1482, and at Venice in the same year. An edition, published at Venice in 1492, contained, besides, notes by Mancinellus (Antonio Mancinelli, born at Velletri in 1452, a teacher at Orvieto).
